      <h2>Event Bus</h2>
         <p>The <em>event bus</em> is a back-end process that relies on OpenMQ (<a href="https://mq.dev.java.net/">https://mq.dev.java.net/</a>) to allow the interchange of events between the different ALIVE components. OpenMQ is shipped along the ALIVE bundle installation, so a local <em>event bus</em> process can be easily configured and set to run.</p>
         <p> Thus, all the components on the monitoring system, and some external ones (such as the agents on Coordination level) rely on the <em>event bus</em>.</p>
         <h3>Step Through</h3>
      <h4>Configuration</h4>
         <p><em>Event bus</em> configuration can be specified via the <em>runtime dashboard</em>. There, users can specify the location of the <em>event bus</em> back-end process to be used. By default the <em>event bus</em> back-end process is running on the local machine.</p>
<h4>Running</h4>
         <p><em>Event bus</em> can be started via the <em>Start</em> <em>Event Bus</em> button on the <em>runtime dashboard</em>, or via the start-up script contained on the OpenMQ installation folder. <br />
Assuming OpenMQ has been installed on <em>$Open_MQ_HOME$ </em>the event bus can be started running the following scripts:</p>
         <ul>
           <li>On Windows: <em>$Open_MQ_HOME$/mq/bin/imqbrokerd.exe â€“tty</em></li>
           <li>On Mac: <em>$Open_MQ_HOME$/mq/bin/imqbrokerd.sh -tty</em></li>
         </ul>
         <p>Either way of starting the event bus will effectively create an event bus back-end process that enables exchange of events.</p>
